result.execSummary:
The defendant Caitlyn F Doepel was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Criminal Damage to Property [Modifiers: PTAC, as a Party to a Crime], a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 943.01(1).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

miscConds.notes: If probation or extended supervision is revoked or discharged with outstanding financial obligations, a civil judgment shall be entered against the defendant and in favor of restitution victims and governmental entities for the balance due.  Collections may include income assignment.  This applies to all counts and financial obligations.

Obey all of the rules and regulations of supervising probation agent.  Pay supervision fees.  Do not possess or consume alcoholic beverages and do not have alcoholic beverages within the residence.  Do not possess or consume controlled substances, except by prescription or paraphernalia.    Participate in counseling deemed appropriate by your agent, which may include: alcohol/drug, anger management/DV counseling, psychiatric/psychological, AODA Assessment and follow-through with recommended treatment.
**   Pay all court costs including all applicable surcharges.  If unpaid financial obligations remain at discharge or revocation, civil judgment to be entered.  Submit a DNA sample (unless previously provided).
** Pay DNA surcharge.

records.addlTxt: Attorney Jessica Krejcarek appeared for the State. Atty K Noonan appeared on behalf of deft, who did not appear. Clerk/H. Barnett. Atty Noonan withdraws petition for expunction. ADA Krejcarek states there is still an outstanding warrant in IL. No action taken.

Attorney Jessica Krejcarek appeared for the State. Defendant appeared in court in person and w/ Attorney K Noonan. Clerk/H. Barnett. Expunction hearing. Atty Noonan states the deft's case in IL was resolved, deft completed probation there and is also seeking expunction in that case. Based on Lake County IL circuit court access it appears there is an outstanding warrant. ADA Krejcarek states she believes the deft is ineligible for expunction due to a conviction subsequent to this case and as the deft did not successfully complete probation. Expunction hearing continued to 5/16/18 at 8:30am; deft to produce proof that IL case is completed and documentation from her counselor of her progress.
